body:
Someone give me a low-DTE overnight play, since my I'm at my fucking 3 ~~fucking~~ day trade limit.  And don't say AMD, ya fucks.

&amp;#x200B;

Edit: re-ordered words, didn't like the flow

Thank you!

&amp;#x200B;

What was your strike and  DTE?  I've been looking at 0-3DTE, but it means I'm putting on more risk.

Ok you're CLEARLY a complete and utter RETARD. The problem with this is that your focusing on what my options will be worth AT EXPIRATION. Nobody fucking holds until expiration. It's absurd that you thought I would. No shit, most options expire worthless. That's why I buy 2 months out, because it gives me plently of time for the stock to move in my direction and get out a few weeks early if it doesn't go my way. 

&amp;#x200B;

&gt;**That's incredibly wrong.** Here's an AAPL 385 call 45 days/1.5 months DTE: [https://imgur.com/a/Mo35i8Z](https://imgur.com/a/Mo35i8Z). Although it's a $385 call, it needs to reach $394 or higher to even **BREAK EVEN** at expiry.

This chart is AT EXPIRATION. Also, break even only applies to AT EXPIRATION. You can sell options before expiration which almost everyone does. This is enough evidence for me to realize that you're a complete retard and probably very new to options trading. No experienced trader would mention break even unless you plan on excercising the option. I don't have enough capital to buy 100 shares of AAPL or SPY, sorry. 

&amp;#x200B;

&gt;an additional factor is that you're long Vega **AND** you're expecting an increase in the price. This doesn't make a lot of sense since you're expecting the stock price to increase. 

No, volatility isn't a huge issue for me, and I don't see why it is for you either. As long as volatility stays relativily close, I'll have no problems. I'm not an idiot and I don't buy 80%+ IV options. 

&amp;#x200B;

&gt;**Yes, it is extremely different.** It's your risk and chance to profit and the amount of theta you incur. ITM has little to no theta whereas OTM has MASSIVE theta. That's an extremely powerful difference between the two. 

Maybe very OTM but as I stated before, I only buy slightly OTM. Also, I buy 2 months out so theta is not an issue at all for me. Again, I'm not holding until expiration. My goal is that the stock moves in my direction within the next month or so and I get out. Theta is not much greater than ITM in this case. 

&amp;#x200B;

&gt; **The house always wins if you're only going to buy options without an informational advantage or a stroke of luck.**

Not really, you're telling me the run up we've had due to the FED and QE is a "stroke of luck". My asshole. Obviously now that everything is at ATH or past ATH it's difficult to tell where we're headed but up until then it's not luck. It's a matter of identifying the trend and trading it, it's really not hard. 

&amp;#x200B;

&gt;**I'm only frustrated because you think you're using a strategy with very good risk/reward ratios, but if you refer to the profit/loss options graph, you can see that the risk reward is actually dreadful** especially since gains are infinitely linear while stock movements on the tail-end of the spectrum are exponentially less likely to occur, despite your infinite potential returns that scale only linearly.

ONLY AT EXPIRATION. This is true if I was a complete idiot and held until expiration. I don't do that. If it goes in my direction and hits my profit target, I get out. 

&amp;#x200B;

&gt;Buying options naked is a **BAD** strategy in terms of risk/reward. You can't deny this. You can say that, given your insight into the market, you do have an informational and flexibility advantage as opposed to institutional investors limited to lower-risk, more diversification, mass-liquidity limited choices of investment vehicles.

There is no such thing as buying naked. There is selling naked but not buying. It's actually a very profitable strategy if you buy the dips on a clear uptrend like i've been doing. 

&amp;#x200B;

&gt; And this doesn't cover other strategies like the Jade Lizard, where there's no upside risk, reward ATM, and double loss below the money

Stop trying to get me you to use your shitty strategies. I've got better things to do than learn what the fuck a "Jade Lizard" is. If it works for you, good on you. But I would rather capture larger gains without having to execute multiple legs and capping my gains. Also, it's difficult to assess whether I'm getting a good price with spreads whereas with simple calls I can view the price history and immediately tell if I'm getting a good value historically. 

&amp;#x200B;

&gt;**Buying an option is inherently unprofitable. No single option has over a 50% chance to profit.** An ATM option is only profitable 33% of the time on average for the buyer, and 67% profitable for the seller. An OTM option is around 20% or less profitable for the buyer. There is no such thing as high profitability options buying unless you mean ATM compared to FD.

No, you can literally view a particular option's price history and determine what it will be worth. That's how I know how much I will multiply my investment by. I can't do this with spreads. And once again, I'm not waiting until expiration so what you said isn't true at all. The fact that you fail to understand that options can be sold before expiration proves that you don't understand what I'm talking about. 

&amp;#x200B;

&gt;The risk is also 100% of your capital. Just because your capital is low doesn't mean the strategy is low risk. You're using a high risk, low probability of profit, moderate return (with a potential of infinite return if expectations are greatly exceeded) strategy. It is inherently high risk low profitability by its nature. If you buy an ITM call on AAPL right now at $350, your chance to profit is 46%. The safest kind of investment as far as ONLY buying options is concerned. There is less risk because you only lose 100% of your investment if the price tanks a shit ton and ends up below $350. Otherwise, you get to keep some of your capital. OTM is inherently much higher risk because of this; you'll probably lose your entire investment if it doesn't end up profitable.

&amp;#x200B;

THIS IS COMPLETELY WRONG. All you have to do is look at a particular option's price history to see that you can make multiple times on your money if it goes in your dirrection. Again, sell BEFORE expiration. 

I can't believe you actually think that I hold until expiration. Nobody does this. That's why I think you're having trouble understanding the profitibility of my strategy. You don't have a basic understanding of options, even though you act like you do.

always whichever is closest to the money. if SPY is at 337.44 but overbought, RSI is high, and bullish trend is converging, I'll buy a 337 put (or 2, or 3). It's effective. I mean, sometimes I only make like $5-6 per. but when you do it 30x throughout the day, it can really add up.

&amp;#x200B;

Edit: Another reason I don't buy 0 DTE is because if I am behind on a contract at the end of the day that I still think has a chance, I can sell it for better salvage the next day or even make money. It happened this morning with 333 calls that I bought yesterday. was able to make an extra $107.

&gt;Stop buying weeklies and move to 21-45DTE.

&amp;#x200B;

Unless you're going to start taking profits on any gains immediately, try 45 DTE minimum, ideally 60+
